- Step 7 (wretched 4 7 8 2) turns next(object_4,object_7) into next(object_4,object_8).
- Step 8 (tightfisted 10 4 8) requires vase(object_10,object_4), sneeze(object_4), texture(object_8) and next(object_4,object_8) — all satisfied — and produces next(object_10,object_8).

Why next(object_9,object_6) is unreachable
- Which actions can add a fact next(9, X)?
  - paltry adds next(h, o2) but paltry requires cats(object_1) on the second argument. In the initial state the only cats fact is cats object_0, so paltry(9, *, *) can only have its second parameter = object_0. That means paltry can only add next(9, Y) where Y is whatever object_0 currently points to (initially 5; with memory it can become 7). So paltry can produce next(9,5) or next(9,7) at best — never next(9,6).
  - tightfisted adds next(h, o2) but requires a vase(h, o1) where o1 is a sneeze object and an existing next(o1, o2). To get next(9,6) via tightfisted you would need a vase(9, s) with s a sneeze object that has next(s,6). The only sneeze object that has next(.,6) initially is object_3 (next(object_3,object_6)). So you would need vase(9,object_3).
- How to get vase(9,object_3)?
  - sip creates vase(h, object_0) only (the second arg must be the cats object_0), so sip cannot create vase(9,3).
  - clip can create a vase(h, o1) where o1 is a sneeze object, but clip(h,o1,o2) requires both next(o1,o2) and next(h,o2) to exist already. To create vase(9,3) via clip you would need a p such that next(3,p) and next(9,p) are both present. That requires next(9,p) to exist before you can create the vase you need to create next(9,6) — circular.
- Therefore there is no non-circular way to produce the needed vase(9,3) and thus no way to apply tightfisted to get next(9,6). Paltry cannot produce it either (paltry's second arg is restricted to object_0). No other action produces next facts with first argument 9. Conclusion: next(object_9,object_6) is unreachable.

That confines a sneeze object's next to stay inside its initial collect-group (wretched cannot move a sneeze object's next from Group A to Group B or vice versa).
- For a hand-object to adopt a new next you must use paltry (hand with a cat) or tightfisted (hand with a sneeze). Both paltry and tightfisted require a vase(hand,partner) to exist. A vase is created either by sip (hand + cat) or clip (hand + sneeze). Both sip and clip require that the hand and the partner currently share the same next target (next(hand, t) and next(partner, t)), so to create a vase with a sneeze you must already have next(hand) equal to next(sneeze).

  - sip(hand, catY, Z) requires both next(hand, Z) and next(catY, Z) (it creates vase(hand, catY) but only if next(hand,Z) already held).
- Therefore: to create a new vase(hand, ·) for a hand H, either H must already have next(H, Z) for some Z (so clip/sip can be applied) or an existing vase(hand, ·) must already be present. - Consider the goal next(object_13, object_10). object_13 is a hand. The only ways to add next(object_13, object_10) are paltry or tightfisted for object_13 (memory/wretched don't act on hands). So you cannot create the vase needed to later add next(object_13, object_10) unless next(object_13, Z) already matched the sneeze/cat you want to use. In the initial state object_13 points to object_7; the sneeze objects point only to textures in their collect-group (object_4 to {6,7,8}, object_5 to {9,10,11}). To get a vase(object_13, object_5) (needed to use tightfisted with sneeze 5 and then follow to 10), you would need next(object_13, Z) = next(object_5, Z) for some Z — that is not true initially, and there is no way to make object_13 share a Z with object_5 without already having the vase (the same circular dependency). Concretely: object_13 cannot gain the vase with sneeze 5 or with any cat that points to 10, because no cat points to 10 and you cannot create the needed vase without next(object_13, 10) already holding. So next(object_13, object_10) is unreachable.

- Some hand-target goals are reachable by the pattern used in your first plan: if a hand H already shares a next-target Z with some sneeze S, then clip(H,S,Z) can create vase(H,S), then wretched can move S among textures in S's collect-group, and tightfisted(H,S,T) can set next(H,T).   - Hands that do NOT initially share a next-target with any sneeze/cat cannot get the necessary vase to use paltry/tightfisted, so their desired next facts cannot be created.

Conclusion
- Because at least one required goal next(object_13, object_10) is unreachable under the given rules and initial facts, there is no valid plan that achieves the entire goal set you asked for.
- If you want a satisfiable instance, two simple ways to make it possible:

  2. Add an initial vase(object_13, object_5) (or vase(object_13, some cat) together with next(cat, object_10)), so paltry/tightfisted can be used to add next(object_13, object_10).
